The Economy of Violence
KOPENHAGEN – What is the greatest source of violence in our world?
Brutal conflicts in Syria, in Ukraine, and elsewhere are constantly a topic in the news, and therefore many would probably say war.
However, this proves to be a great mistake.
The correct answer plays a role when we want to find cost-effective solutions for this and other global problems.
It is obvious that everyone would like to end every war and act of violence, just as we would like to see an end to poverty, hunger, and climate change, and provide access to education for all people.
However, in view of limited resources, there are limits to what the international community can do.
We must set priorities and for this you can use an economic cost-benefit analysis.
The international community is working on new development goals for the next 15 years, and the Copenhagen Consensus asked some of the world's leading economists to evaluate which goals they consider to be the most sensible.
Is the goal of reducing violence worth the expenditure of resources that would otherwise, for example, be used to combat hunger?
And, if so, which forms of violence should be targeted?
According to a study by James Fearon from Stanford University and Anke Höffler from the Center for the Study of African Economies at Oxford University, violence in society – murders and above all violence against women and children – is a far greater problem than civil wars.
For every death on the battlefield of a civil war, nine people die from interpersonal violence, and for every two combatants who die, one child is killed.
In 2008, 418,000 people were killed worldwide, and far too many countries register murder rates of over 10 victims per 100,000 inhabitants, which the World Health Organization classifies as an epidemic.
One single murder in America costs a person his life and society 9.1 million US dollars.
Measured against the national income of the world, this form of violent crime costs 1.7% of the global gross domestic product (GDP).
Naturally, this is not a direct financial loss for the global economy, but rather a way to express the consequences.
If murders could be abolished, societies worldwide would be better off in a way that can be quantified at 1.7% of GDP.
Compare this to the significantly lower costs of civil wars, which correspond to around 0.2% of the world's GDP.
This is still much less than the greatest source of violence of all: domestic violence against women.
Based on studies published in the scientific journal Science, 28% of all women in sub-Saharan Africa last year experienced violence from their partners or family members.
This includes women who were beaten, married off at a young age, subjected to sexual violence, victims of crimes in the name of "honor," and those who underwent female genital mutilation.
According to a cautious estimate, the social costs of violence from partners alone amount to 4.4 trillion US dollars or 5.2% of the global GDP.
The second-largest source of violence is child abuse, which is carried out by parents 80% of the time.
The definition of child abuse varies from culture to culture, but around 15% of children experience each month what the UN classifies as severe physical punishment.
To this belong face slaps, head slaps or ear slaps, and a quarter of these children are repeatedly and as severely as possible hit with an object.
Every month, this suffering falls over around 290 million children.
The social costs amount to 3.6 trillion US dollars or 4.2% of the global GDP.
A tiny fraction of international aid funds currently flows into reducing violence in society and improving criminal justice systems.
The enormous costs borne by society and individuals cry out for action to be taken.
Unfortunately, there are still hardly any secure findings on where the limited funds should be used best.
What can be said is that the money spent on reducing violence could be used more effectively.
Large amounts of aid money are destined for „fragile states“ to contribute to ending or preventing civil wars, yet only 0.27% of international aid goes to projects with the component „crime prevention“.
Other programs can make a contribution indirectly, but clearly, much could be done better.
Certain solutions are clearly functioning very well.
More effective social institutions can reduce violence against children.
Studies in the US state of Washington have shown that visits from trained staff can reduce child abuse, improve the quality of life of children, and their physical and mental health, and can reduce the costs of care and procedural costs.
A dollar spent on this program produces a benefit worth 14 US dollars: It is thus a very cost-effective measure.
In many cases, societal attitudes must change.
To reduce violence against women and girls, a program in Uganda called SASA! is underway.
(Kisuaheli for "Now!") for spreading the idea that violence in the partnership is unacceptable and has contributed to halving the number of cases.
This is a fantastic result, even if there is no analysis of cost-effectiveness.
There are examples from other countries where effective measures have been taken.
In 1993, there were 80 murders per 100,000 inhabitants in Bogotá.
With a comprehensive approach - a time limit for the sale of alcohol, the recovery of public space and improvements in the police and justice system - the murder rate was reduced to 21 victims per 100,000 inhabitants in 2004.
That's still a high number, but far below the murder rate of 55 victims per 100,000 residents in Detroit.
Alcohol plays a role in many physical attacks and the findings from Bogotá suggest that controlling its availability could be of major importance.
In the United Kingdom, a pilot study on better enforcement of existing regulations has shown that physical attacks could be reduced in a very cost-effective manner, with a benefit-to-cost ratio of 17 to one.
We still don't know enough, but two points are clear: Firstly, domestic violence against women and children involves costs of 8 billion US dollars per year to society and thus constitutes a huge – and far too little recognized – global problem.
Secondly, there are solutions that can contribute to addressing some of these problems in a very cost-effective manner.
For this reason, reducing domestic violence should be a priority for the world's next development goals.
